annotations:
I’m as calm as a baby lamb that is being led
 I’m as blue as blood before the blood goes red
They’re managing now, but they won’t always be able to. In other words: it’s the calm before the storm (emotionally).

But there’s a hunger under my skin, and it’s gripping at my bones
 There’s a hunger like a lion’s, and it’s ripping right through my bones
As much as they want to be satisfied alone, they crave the feeling that they have when they’re with that person. The rush, the intimacy, and the desire to live.

The parts that are dormant, I wish to set them free
 And in the clarity of this night, I make myself believe I can sleep easily alone
Now they hope to hold onto this feeling once they’re alone.

We ripped off all our clothes, and this included all our jewelry
 And we ran hand in hand back when you brought out the beast in me
The narrator wants to want to live. These moments, sexual and intimate, that they spent with another person made them aware of what people live for.

I pressed my ear against your back not even a week after we met
 And I felt your heartbeat fall like raindrops in a bucket
The songwriter is reflecting on a moment in their budding relationship. The concept of the heartbeat, representing aliveness, returns later in the song.
Twist your hips and crane your neck
If we’re ready to get better, a simple place to start is by letting yourself dance and lifting your head up in order to gain the self-confidence to finally pursue it.
You’ve gotta be starving, you’ve gotta be starving for it

We have to want to get better to truly start to recover and progress. To reach the height of our potential, we need to be starved for self-improvement and reach our lowest points before we can truly want it the most.
It is a God-damned joke how we can hurt even in the sun
Pondering how we can feel such pain even when circumstances are seemingly good, and we have natural blessings like the sun.

I used to have a pretty nice spine, but I neglected to give it a name
 So each time I tried to straighten it, I couldn’t get its attention
Spine symbolizes confidence and bravery, which the narrator hasn’t used or acknowledged to their full potential. The metaphorical slouch is a habitual lack of confidence/bravery.

description.plain:
A song is a private piece of heaven, and Lady Lamb promises to pour her life and blood into sharing her song with us.  This album is a far more intimate undertaking than her previous work.  It is something between her, in the lights on the stage, and the unseen listener in the dark balcony lost in the heaven of her song.

Lady Lamb is selling her song as the prostitute in Olympia sells her body, but she gives it, “Trying to be good.  Trying to be kind.  Trying to stay true.”  This is an opening to the album; let her sing and spill her heart out fighting to bring you closer to heaven.

It is something between her, in the lights on the stage, and the unseen listener in the dark balcony lost in the heaven of her song.

annotations:
I will protect your solitude
 I’ll keep first watch over our expanse

A reference to Rainer Maria Rilke, translated by Stephen Mitchell in ‘Rilke on Love’

“The point of marriage is not to create a quick commonality by tearing down all boundaries; on the contrary, a good marriage is one in which each partner appoints the other to be the guardian of his solitude, and thus they show each other the greatest possible trust. A merging of two people is an impossibility, and where it seems to exist, it is a hemming-in, a mutual consent that robs one party or both parties of their fullest freedom and development. But once the realization is accepted that even between the closest people infinite distances exist, a marvelous living side-by-side can grow up for them, if they succeed in loving the expanse between them, which gives them the possibility of always seeing each other as a whole and before an immense sky.”

Solitude and guardianship also the subject of Letter #7 in ‘Letters to a Young Poet’.
Olympia 1865

Manet’s painting titled “Olympia” was first exhibited in 1865. It caused great controversy at the time, because it depicts a nude prostitute with a confrontational gaze.



Why Lady Lamb refers to the painting in the song is not clear. Could it be that the sleeping person whose head she cradles reminds her of the model in the painting (even though the model has brown eyes)?

description.plain:
In an interview with Glide Magazine, Aly describes the crux of the song as yearning for a connection, particularly in the scope of a musician’s life on the road:

“The song came out of thinking about what it’s like to be away from home and missing home and being comforted by home,” she says. “It’s sort of about the duality of wanting to connect with people and wanting to be introspective and quiet. Wanting to be out in the world and also wanting to be home in your own space."

body.plain:
In an interview with Glide Magazine, Aly describes the crux of the song as yearning for a connection, particularly in the scope of a musician’s life on the road:

“The song came out of thinking about what it’s like to be away from home and missing home and being comforted by home,” she says. “It’s sort of about the duality of wanting to connect with people and wanting to be introspective and quiet. Wanting to be out in the world and also wanting to be home in your own space."

annotations:
It’s June where you sleep, July where I land
 Thought I saw you on the platform in Amsterdam
 And I nearly missed my train
 And I felt so defeated ’til I jumped on to see
 All the warm smiles were for me yeah

The singer is exhausted by this leg of her tour, seeing the partner she misses (or a friend) in unexpected places, despite this person being on the other side of the world. Barely making her train quickly shifts her mood for the better when she sees the smiles of its passengers; being reminded of the kindness of strangers and with that, the world.
I just want to fall into a pile of warm laundry
The singer misses being home, longing for the simple pleasures of home life; like falling into a pile of freshly dried laundry.

I check my phone for the time but I still wear my watch
 Yeah, i’m confused about how
 I’m supposed to connect to anything now

The singer laments on her inability to adapt with the constant changing of technology. Despite having a clock on her phone, it’s familiar and more comfortable for her to do things as she’s always done. She’s not quite sure how to truly make connections with other human beings in an era where we’re less connected than ever before (despite the illusion that we are.)

Still this feels like eating the meat of the mountain
 It’s all grit and gristle I can’t chew and swallow
 I’m gnawing my way back home

Of these lyrics, Aly Spaltro says “That I wrote on tour. I was on a tour I was not enjoying very much and was really homesick out in the middle of the mountains, very far from home. I thought it was an interesting visual for the feeling that you have when you’re driving in the opposite direction of the direction you want to go in. You know what I mean? I was up in the mountains, just going further and further away. I felt like eating the meat of the mountain, gnawing my way through the road to get home.”

http://allstonpudding.com/interview-lady-lamb/

Some days I can only see into my suitcase
 It’s got everything I need
 Plus some superstitious things I may also need

When asked about what the superstitious things were in an interview, Aly Spaltro said they were  “Little, silly things like a T-shirt, a hat, cut-outs that I’ve tapped to the inside of my suitcase. If someone gives me a trinket on tour, that becomes a thing that I carry with me for the rest of tour. I’m sure people who leave home a lot do this — keep little things that comfort.”
http://www.citypages.com/music/indie-rocker-lady-lamb-dont-call-me-twee-7605739
This links back into the song’s exploration of seeking comfort and connection, and the strangeness of how we go about that – while maybe not the most practical, this is something grounding for her while on tour

The kind of high I like is when I barely make the train
 And the people with a seat smile big at me
 Because they know the feelin’
 And for a millisecond we share a look like a family does
 Like we have inside jokes
 Like we could call each other by little nicknames
 And I could tell the story of how
 My great grandmother’s sister was deemed a saint
 How they exhumed her body after years of being buried
 And they found she hadn’t even begun’ to sully
 So they moved her again, straight into the Vatican

Here Aly draws a comparison between the brief moment of connection felt with these passengers to the way it feels being surrounded by family, and showing affection through shared stories, jokes, and “little nicknames.” Plus, turns out it is a true story about her great grandmother’s sister :)

“That’s a story from the Italian side of my family, on my dad’s side. She died when she was a little girl. They had to exhume her body, and some others, from where she was buried, and move them, and they found she was entirely intact when they exhumed her.  And they were shocked and they made a note of it. They checked her again because they believe in that kind of thing–the incorruptibility of bodies to mean holiness or saintliness. And the next time they exhumed her they found that she still hadn’t decomposed so they ending up deeming her a saint and burying her in the Vatican.”

I think of all the billions of eyes
 All looking at something different at the same time
 And I feel nauseous
This can be described by the word “Sonder” – the awareness that everyone around you is also experiencing the same world you are, but differently.

annotations: Now I only have eyes for you, you are the apple, you are the apple

This could have a potential dual meaning. The phrase “you are the apple of my eye” refers to a person one loves so intensely, they’re held above all others. She’s been known to use a lot of biblical allegory in her lyrics, so this line could also be referring to the Apple of Eden. In eating the apple after commanded not to by God, Eve creates the original sin and is banished along with Adam from the Garden of Eden. As is previously hinted at in the last verse, she’s struggling with understanding her own sexuality. This woman she’s referencing is that Apple of Eden, the thing she desires that she has either been told she can’t have, or has convinced herself is wrong to want.
Your eyes so close that I could hide in the closet, hide in the closet
This alludes to her sexuality, having thoughts of another girl make her want to “hide in the closet” and not face who she is.

I’d’ve been fine with that
 ’cause it would have saved me, yes, it would have saved me
 It would have saved me, yes, it would have saved me
 It would have saved me, yes, it would have saved me
 It would have saved me from the look that you gave
 When you left
She’s saying she’d even be okay with dying if it meant not remembering how she was left alone by her lover.

description.plain:
Of the many ways we abuse ourselves for unrequited love; we lower ourselves into the vegetable kingdom with seeds to bury in the ground when we might rise as birds into the air.

Royal purple sheets only remind our lady of what she cannot reach.  But the conflicted nature of the potent desire and potential relationship war against the Christian ethics of the person making her feel this way, and prevent even admission of yearning for such a carnal relationship as the linen demands.  And so the lady is left hurt and hurting herself over “a heart that won’t show its face.”

We’ve Got A Good Thing Going Lyrics[Intro]
I climbed to the top of the Pyramid of the Sun
Thought the height would make me feel alright
But the view of the Avenue of the Dead
Didn't get my blood pumpin' again
So I bent over the body of the volcano
Saw it flood itself with its own warmth
And just on the other side of that mesmerizing light
There I stood, feelin' jealous

'Cause I just want to show my friends what I have for them
I have my whole heart for them
So why am I hidin' in my room again?
This always happens
I'm afraid I've misplaced the strength to not give a shit
[Verse 1]
The other night I watched a woman free fall
From the top of the third tallest tower in the world
She raised her arms like an angel
Then she stepped off the platform without hesitation
The wind held her there in midair for a second
I think she stands for the ecstatic gift of life
And there's a cause for celebration
If I open my eyes

[Chorus]
I'll take all the living you can give me
Yeah, we've got a good thing goin'

[Verse 2]
We've got a good thing going, yeah
I wanna be alive for the rest of my life
To feel the gratitude in givin' everything I am
Without a promise of anything in return
To feel melodies unwritten
I am living to sing

[Chorus]
I'll take all the living you can give me
Yeah, we've got a good thing goin'
You might also like[Bridge]
We've got a good thing going, yeah
I'll sing of our joys and our sorrows
With the band or on my own
That's what we've been given love
It's the blushes and the boredom
The flesh and the blood
It's the endless sprawl
We've climbed up to fall
So we may as well just feel it all
Let's feel it get heavy
Then let's make it a weight that we can carry

[Outro]
I'll take all the living you can give me
Yeah, we've got a good thing goin'
We've got a good thing goin'
We've got a good thing goin'
We've got a good thing goin'
We've got a good thing goin'Embed
